= Regular Install = 
1. Run "build toolchain"  from the compile folder. The files generated are
placed in "built" in the main folder. 
2. Copy the files inside "built" in  "doc/toolchain"  in the project   



= New Documentation install
1. See above
2. See above

3. Define the documentation title, source folder and other ant properties
   in manual.xml. Bellow is a minimal file for the documentation.
   
 ->  imports
  
 build.xml -> manual.xml -> doc.xml -> doc_paths.xml
                                    -> after_properties.xml

Example: 

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project name="doc.IC2D">
    <property name="doc.name"               value="IC2D" />
    <property name="docs.src.dir"           value="../doc/src_ic2d" />

     <!-- ##used for DocBookize## -->
    <!-- the path for java file inclusion -->
    <property name="java.inclusion" value="${src.proactive.dir}/${proactive.path}" />

    <property name="xml.inclusion" value="${descriptors.dir}/" />

    <!-- The path to find java files in html -->
    <property name="otherpath1.inclusion" value="ProActive_src_html/${proactive.path}/" /> <!-- broken -->

    <property name="otherpath2.inclusion" value="${src.examples.dir}/${proactive.path}/" />
    <property name="otherpath3.inclusion" value="./"/>
    <property name="otherpath4.inclusion" value="./"/>
    <property name="otherpath5.inclusion" value="./"/>

    <import file="toolchain/doc.xml"/>
</project>

    
   
4. Create after_properties.xml for properties or targets that need previous defined properties
   or targets as for example javadoc targets. 

    
Several documentation projects can coexist at the same time in the same project by dynamically changing
the ant properties in manual.xml and after_properties.xml (project name, source folder, etc).  One way
to set several documentations is creating ant tasks that copy predefined settings files to manual.xml
and after_properties.xml.
